@PizlaTheDeveloper Thanks for digging this out.

Because of https://github.com/grpc/grpc/blob/16316a9fec3a78baf83d96dbdb392e90226bb013/src/python/grpcio/grpc/_channel.py#L682, I was making the assumption that grpc would always exhaust the request generator before ending the iteration of the response, and thought this would always be called:
https://github.com/googlesamples/assistant-sdk-python/commit/187b485afd5c5df8288a135108065d963a201a84#diff-7262ae17d2cea4f6cb6c2b5934aaf939L127

But it looks like it's not the case! and that the iteration on `self.assistant.Assist` responses can finish before `iter_assist_requests` is exhausted. (Maybe @nathanielmanistaatgoogle can shed some light on the expected behavior).

@PizlaTheDeveloper can you give a try at https://github.com/googlesamples/assistant-sdk-python/pull/188/commits/2dfc868ebce1b78f772afe1af174337cc2de4ebc I added explicit locking to make sure we can safely close the recording stream from the main thread.

You can test the following script:

```python
print "Using list: all fine"
dicc = {'key1': 'value1', 'key2': 'value2'}
for key in dicc.keys():
    print "pop", dicc.pop(key)
print "dicc", dicc

print "Using iterator: RuntimeError: dictionary changed size during iteration"
dicc = {'key1': 'value1', 'key2': 'value2'}
for key in dicc.iterkeys():
    print "pop", dicc.pop(key)
print "dicc", dicc
```
